From: vyos-ls1046a-build M3-3 step 4 v3 <noreply@vyos-ls1046a-build>
Date: 2026-05-28
Subject: [PATCH] dpaa: NAPI-hooked BMan refill from the XSK fill ring (v3: stand-alone, absorbs 0086+0087)

M3-3 step 4 (spec sec 6.1.3, "NAPI-hooked BMan refill"). Wires the
xsk_pool fill-ring -> BMan-pool top-up loop into the per-CPU NAPI
poll's tail, immediately after xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup arming. Pure
additive change; with no XSK pool bound (default flavor) the new
flavor-op callback is a NULL deref under RCU and the rest of the
loop walks zero qbands. With a pool bound (vpp flavor + xsk_bind),
the callback drains the XSK fill ring into the BMan pool in
hardware-correct 8-buffer release windows.

Three coordinated changes:

  1. New ops->napi_refill callback on struct dpaa_qmgmt_ops.
     Added to dpaa_flavor.h after xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup. The
     flavor module iterates priv->xsk_bpool[] internally.

  2. Call site in dpaa_eth_poll().
     Folded into the EXISTING rcu_read_lock() region that hosts the
     xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup call. No additional RCU section, no
     additional ops dereference -- the local `ops` from the prior
     rcu_dereference() is reused.

  3. New u64 xsk_bman_refill_batches counter on struct dpaa_priv,
     exposed via ethtool -S as "xsk_bman_refill_batches".
     Bumped once per non-empty xsk_buff_alloc_batch() round-trip
     (the 8-buffer BMan release chunks within one round-trip count
     as a single batch).

Flavor-module body (af_xdp_pool_main.c) -- af_xdp_pool_napi_refill():

  Walks priv->xsk_max_qbands. For each bound (priv->xsk_bpool[qband]
  non-NULL) qband:
    - Single-CPU pin: only priv->qmap[q].cpu drives this qband
      (raw_smp_processor_id() check) so the XSK FILL ring's SPSC
      producer cursor stays single-writer.
    - RCU-deref priv->xsk_pool[qband]; skip if NULL.
    - xsk_buff_alloc_batch() into stack handles[32]/bmbs[32]
      (10 KiB per-call stack footprint, well within NAPI budget).
    - For each handle: pre-zero bmbs[i].data (CRITICAL: see below),
      then bm_buffer_set64() with the XSK chunk's DMA address.
    - Release in 8-buffer chunks (CRITICAL: see below).
    - Bump priv->xsk_bman_refill_batches if n > 0.

THREE BMAN HW CONTRACTS, all enforced in this single patch:

  (a) BMan RCR (Release Command Ring) verb byte BUFCOUNT field is
      4 bits wide (bman.c:116 BUFCOUNT_MASK = 0x0f). bman_release()
      asserts num in [1,8] (bman.c:746). Any value > 8 produces a
      malformed RCR command verb that the QBMan portal silently
      rejects with "ErrInt: Invalid Command Verb" (BM_EIRQ_IVCI).
      DPAA_ASSERT() is a no-op without CONFIG_FSL_DPAA_CHECKING=y
      so this corruption is silent on production builds. The
      release loop below releases at most 8 buffers per
      bman_release() call. Mainline dpaa_eth.c:1624 uses the same
      8-buffer chunk pattern.

  (b) bman_release() composes the RCR slot as follows:
        bm_buffer_set64(r->bufs, bm_buffer_get64(bufs));   // slot 0 addr
        bm_buffer_set_bpid(r->bufs, pool->bpid);            // slot 0 bpid
        if (i)
            memcpy(&r->bufs[1], &bufs[1], i * sizeof(bufs[0]));
      Only slot 0 gets the pool->bpid override. Slots 1..n-1 are
      memcpied verbatim -- INCLUDING the bpid bits in their high
      word. If the caller's bm_buffer was allocated on the stack
      without zeroing, those bpid bytes contain stack residue
      which BMan validates and rejects as IVCI. The pre-zero
      `bmbs[i].data = 0;` below mirrors mainline's
      dpaa_bp_add_8_bufs() idiom (dpaa_eth.c:1639).

  (c) FILL-ring empty / double-release invariant (spec sec 6.1.8).
      The userspace probe oops on 2026-05-28 demonstrated that a
      broken userspace recycle (writing to FILL without checking
      its own consumer cursor) can deposit the same UMEM chunk
      twice. xsk_buff_alloc_batch() then returns the same xdp_buff
      twice, and a naive driver would issue bman_release() with two
      copies of the same DMA address. That would land in the BMan
      pool twice -> double-free -> next ingress overwrites the
      first copy still in flight on the RX FQ. The driver-side
      protection is structural: xsk_buff_alloc_batch() returns 0
      cleanly when the FILL ring is empty, and the consumer cursor
      it maintains is the SOLE source of truth for what to deposit
      into BMan. A broken userspace can starve this loop (returns
      0 -> we skip bman_release()), and a broken userspace can
      hand us a duplicate chunk (xsk_buff_alloc_batch() returns it
      twice -> we release it to BMan twice -> BMan validates and
      may IVCI on the second copy, OR worse, silently accepts it
      and we get RX corruption). The driver cannot detect a
      userspace duplicate; that detection belongs in xsk_buff
      core or in disciplined userspace. THIS LOOP IS CORRECT
      under the SPSC contract; if §6.1.8 recurs the root cause is
      userspace, not this code.

Validation gates (DUT, default-flavor ISO):

  G1: priv->xsk_bman_refill_batches and priv->xsk_bman_starve both
      stay 0 across kernel-skbuf line-rate iperf3. Confirms the
      ops->napi_refill walk short-circuits on the
      priv->xsk_bpool[qband] == NULL test.
  G2: dmesg clean, no WARN/BUG/Oops/probe errors, NO
      "bman_ccsr 1890000.bman: ErrInt: Invalid Command Verb".
  G3: ethtool -S eth1 shows "xsk_bman_refill_batches" line.
  G4: iperf3 eth1->lxc200 within single-run jitter of patch 0083's
      929/928 Mbps reference.
  G5 (vpp flavor + xsk_bind): xsk_bman_refill_batches increments,
      xsk_bman_starve stays 0 as long as the userspace recycle
      keeps up, BMan IVCI count stays 0.

v2 (2026-05-27) -- option-c single-CPU pinning. v1 hard-hung the
DUT under sustained load: per-CPU NAPI tails (up to 4 CPUs
concurrently) raced on the XSK fill ring's single-producer cursor
(SPSC by uapi/linux/if_xdp.h contract), corrupting handles[] and
feeding bogus DMA cookies to bman_release(). BMan CCSR rejected
with IVCI; the lockup cascaded into an RCU stall on CPU#3 +
indefinite soft-lockup requiring power-cycle. Fix: each qband
has a single owner CPU (priv->qmap[q].cpu, populated by M3-3 step
2a's per_cpu_ptr() wiring); early-return if raw_smp_processor_id()
!= priv->qmap[q].cpu.

v3 (2026-05-28) -- stand-alone redesign. Absorbs the two post-v2
hot-fix patches (0086 chunked release-by-8, 0087 pre-zero
bmbs[i].data) directly into the seed loop and the napi_refill
loop. v3 also folds in the §6.1.8 FILL-ring invariant comment
and corrects the kerneldoc: the v2 changelog claimed 256-entry
batches but the code declared handles[32]/bmbs[32] (the 32-entry
batch is correct -- 32 chunks * 256-byte XDP buffers = 8 KiB
matching BMan's per-pool stride, and 32 / 8 = 4 release chunks
per round-trip, well within QMan SWP egress depth). Obsolete
references to DPAA1_XSK_REFILL_THRESHOLD / DPAA1_XSK_MIN_DEPTH
are dropped: the public BMan API does not expose a pool depth
query, so depth-driven gating is impossible from this path;
xsk_buff_alloc_batch() return value (0 on empty FILL) is the
natural rate-limit and the only feedback signal available.

